nce":"Blois, Loir-et-Cher, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gaillard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Philippe, Pierre, Andre, Andree, Ketly, Marcel, Mirlande, Monique.","French: nickname from <i>gaillard</i> ‘vigorous, strong’ (ultimately from Celtic <i>galia</i> ‘strength’). This surname (in any of the two possible senses; see also below) is also found in Haiti.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gailhard</i>, composed of the elements <i>gail</i> ‘powerful, lusty, cheerful’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gailliard","meanings":["French: variant of   Gaillard   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Gaylord","meanings":["English (southern, of Norman origin): variant of <b>Gaylard</b> altered by folk etymology, from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Gaillart</i>, <i>Gallard</i>, <i>Galliard</i>, representing either the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gailhard</i> (composed of elements meaning ‘powerful, lusty, cheerful’ + ‘hard, firm, resilient, strong’) or Old French <i>gaillard</i>, <i>gaillart</i> ‘vigorous, powerful, strong’. Alternatively, from Middle English <i>gaillard</i>, <i>galiard</i> ‘brave, strong, valiant’, also ‘lively, gay, gaily dressed’.","Altered form of <b>Gaylard</b>, itself an Anglicized form of French   Gaillard  , which was brought to England by the Huguenots.","In some cases also an Americanized form of French   Gaillard  ."]}]},{"name":"Mathurin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Modern name meaning ‘bear’, a simplified form of the earlier <i>Mathghamhain</i>, borne by a brother of Brian Boru, High King of Ireland in the early 11th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mahon","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Mathúin ."]}]}],"lifeSummary"